				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Conflicts are pretty predictable, generally chips can sink more current than they can source so the bus will be ANDed. The danger is that if a chip's output can source a lot and the other can sink a lot, and somehow this happens frequently enough or the CPU crashes and gets stuck in conflicting state, an output could fry.
<br />
<br />Still there's a slight advantage to using the address bus--you don't need a table:
<br />
<br />*A0-7 are latched*
<br />
<br />LDX banknum
<br />LDA $8x00, X
<br />STA $8x00, X
<br />
<br />VS
<br />
<br />LDA banknum
<br />TAX
<br />STA table, X</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
							</td>
						</tr>
						</table>
					</td>
